'''Ground reinforcement''' is a reinforcing element placed on a flat surface in order to increase accessibility for [[vehicle]]s and ensure proper rainwater drainage in addition to protection<ref>{{cite web|title=Reinforcement Grids for Walkways, Pathways, Car Parks|url=http://www.matsgrids.co.uk/5-ground-reinforcement|website=www.matsgrids.co.uk|language=en}}</ref> The reinforcing element, usually in the form of grids, is used beneath [[grass]], [[asphalt]], [[concrete]] in [[roads]], [[parking lots]], [[driveways]] and [[Sidewalk|paths]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DIY Guide: How To Lay A Gravel Driveway|url=https://www.littlehouseonthecorner.com/lay-a-gravel-driveway/|website=www.littlehouseonthecorner.com}}</ref>

==Materials==
The materials used for ground reinforcement include [[iron]], [[plywood]] and [[recycled plastic]].<ref>http://gridforce.co.uk/grass-protection-grids</ref> [[Recycled plastic]] possesses the desirable properties of water resistance and recycling opportunities, in addition to the [[sustainability]].

==Installation==
Iron plates, being heavy, are generally installed using a [[Crane (machine)|crane]] while [[plywood]] and [[plastic]] reinforcements are placed by hand.

