{{Infobox power station | name = Rwanda Solar Power Station | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Rwanda | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= Location of Rwamagana Solar Power Station | coordinates = {{coord|02|01|34|S|30|22|38|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | relief = no | country = [[Rwanda]] | location = ''Rwamagana'' | status = Operational | construction_began = 2014 | commissioned = 2015<ref name="Open">{{cite web|first=Edwin| url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2015-02-04/185603/| title=Rwamagana 8.5MW Solar Plant To Be Commissioned Today| last=Musoni|accessdate=24 July 2015|date=4 February 2015| newspaper=[[New Vision]]|location=Kigali}}</ref> | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = GigaWatt Global | operator = GigaWatt Global | solar_type = PV | solar_site_area = | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | thermal_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = 8.5&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = | website = | extra = }}
'''Rwamagana Solar Power Station''' is a 8.5MW [[Solar power|solar]] power plant in [[Rwanda]],<ref name="Sign">{{cite web|accessdate=24 July 2015| url=http://rwandaexpress.blogspot.com/2013/07/govt-signs-85mw-solar-energy-deal.html|title=Government Signs 8.5MW Solar Energy Deal| date=22 July 2013|last=RwandaExpress|location=Kigali| newspaper=RwandaExpress Quoting [[New Times (Rwanda)]]}}</ref> the fourth-largest economy in the [[East African Community]].
==Location== The power station is located on leased land, at the campus of ''[[Agahozo Shalom Youth Village]]'', in [[Rwamagana District]], [[Eastern Province, Rwanda|Eastern Rwanda]], approximately {{convert|58|km|0}}, by road, southeast of [[Kigali]], the capital and largest city in the country.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Rwanda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Kigali%2C%20Rwanda&toplace=Agahozo-Shalom%20Youth%20Village%2C%20Rwamagana%2C%20Eastern%20Province%2C%20Rwanda%2C&dt1=ChIJl-fYjiWk3BkRyAsdQaU2K_M&dt2=ChIJtZG__ltO2xkRyCBo1fGhIA4| title=Road Distance Between Kigali And Agahozo-Shalom Youth Village With Route Marker|first=.|last=GFC|accessdate=24 July 2015|date=24 July 2015|publisher=Globefeed.com (GFC)}}</ref> The coordinates of the power station are:2°01'34.0"S, 30°22'38.0"E (Latitude:-2.026111; Longitude:30.377222).<ref>{{google maps|accessdate=24 July 2015| url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/2%C2%B001'34.0%22S+30%C2%B022'38.0%22E/@-1.9243067,29.1564028,6.3z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0?hl=en|title=Location of Rwamagana Solar Power Station At Google Maps}}</ref>
==Overview== In July 2013, the government of Rwanda contracted with GigaWatt Global, a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] firm, to develop an 8.5 Megawatt solar power plant in Rwamagana District, Eastern Province, for a contract price of US$23 million (RwF:15 billion). GigaWatt Global would finance, build, own and operate the facility for 25 years, with the power produced sold to Rwanda Energy, the national electricity utility.<ref name="Sign"/>
In February 2014, GigaWatt Global was able to reach financial closure, allowing construction to begin. Interconnection to the national electricity grid was achieved in July 2014, and by September 2014, the power plant was producing at maximum capacity. The power station consists of 28,360 individual photovoltaic panels spread out on a {{convert|50|acre|ha}} field. The final construction price, including the cost to access the national grid came to US$23.7 million. Funding came from multiple sources, including (a) [[Netherlands Development Finance Company]] (b) Emerging Africa Infrastructure Fund and (c) [[Norfund]]. The United States [[Overseas Private Investment Corporation]] and Finland's Energy and Environment Partnership provided grants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rwa.one/2015/07/19/in-rwanda-israelis-and-americans-launch-east-africas-first-commercial-solar-field/|title=In Rwanda, Israelis And Americans Launch East Africa's First Commercial Solar Field|last=Administrator|first=.|publisher=Rwa.one|date=19 July 2015|accessdate=24 July 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724205059/http://www.rwa.one/2015/07/19/in-rwanda-israelis-and-americans-launch-east-africas-first-commercial-solar-field/|archivedate=24 July 2015|df=}}</ref>
