'''''Syngnathus dawsoni''''' is a species of the [[pipefish]]es. It occurs in the entral, western Atlantic in the [[Caribbean Sea]] from [[Puerto Rico]] to [[St. Lucia]] and has been recorded only from the east of the [[Mona Passage]].<ref name = IUCN/> It is a [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[tropical]] [[demersal fish]]. It is [[ovoviviparous]], te male carries the fertilized eggs n a brood pouch located under his tail.<ref name = FishBase/> It has been captured at around {{convert|7|m|ft}} in shallow, inshore water but its habits and ecology are unknown.<ref name =IUCN/> The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] honours [[Charles Eric Dawson]] who collected the [[Type (biology)|type material]] and who recognised this species as different from the other Atlantic members of the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Syngnathidae]].<ref name = Herald>{{cite journal | author = Herald, E. S. |year = 1969 | title = A new pipefish from the Virgin Islands, ''Micrognathus dawsoni'' | journal = Occasional Papers of the California Academy of Sciences | volume = 73 | pages = 1–3 | url = http://biostor.org/reference/110252/page/3}}</ref>
